    <h2>Part 1: Pre-Production Planning</h2>

    <p>The difference between mediocre and exceptional video content often comes down to planning. Professional creators spend 50% of their time in pre-production, before they ever touch a camera. This is where you define your vision, script your message, and plan every shot.</p>

    <h3>Start With Your Story</h3>
    <p>Every great video begins with a compelling story. Not every video needs a narrative arc, but every video needs a purpose. Before you film anything, ask yourself: What is the point of this video? What do I want my viewers to feel, think, or do after watching?</p>

    <p>Your story should have three clear sections: the hook (grab attention in the first 3 seconds), the body (deliver your value or entertainment), and the call-to-action (tell viewers what to do next). Write this down. Make it specific. Generic videos get scrolled past.</p>

    <p>For example, if you're making a "how-to" video about product photography, your hook might be "Most creators waste $500 on lighting when they could use this $50 trick." Your body shows the actual technique. Your CTA asks viewers to try it and tag you in their results.</p>

