    <h3>Script Your Key Points</h3>
    <p>You don't need a word-for-word script, but you should have an outline. List the key points you want to communicate in order. If you're doing voice-over, write that out word-for-word. Spoken word is harder to edit than visual content—getting it right in-camera saves enormous editing time.</p>

    <p>For on-camera talking head content, practice your lines until you can deliver them naturally without reading. The best performances look casual, but casual takes preparation. Record yourself a few times, watch it back, and refine until you sound like yourself, not a robot.</p>

    <h3>Plan Your Shots</h3>
    <p>Write a shot list. For each scene or section of your video, list the shots you need: wide shots, close-ups, b-roll, graphics, text overlays. A detailed shot list keeps you focused and ensures you don't miss anything on set.</p>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <strong>Pro Tip:</strong> Create a mood board. Find 3-5 reference videos you admire. Study their framing, pacing, color grading, music. Identify specific techniques and recreate them in your own work. This accelerates your learning dramatically.
    </div>

    <h2>Part 2: Lighting Fundamentals</h2>

    <p>Lighting is where amateur video becomes professional video. Bad lighting makes expensive cameras look cheap. Good lighting makes phone cameras look expensive. Master this, and everything else is secondary.</p>

    <h3>The Three-Point Lighting Setup</h3>
    <p>Professional lighting uses three lights: key light, fill light, and back light. The key light (your main light) is positioned 45 degrees to one side of your subject. It creates dimension and shadows. The fill light reduces harsh shadows without eliminating them entirely. The back light separates your subject from the background, creating depth and visual interest.</p>

    <p>You don't need three separate fixtures. A single bright window can be your key light. A white poster board can bounce light back as a fill. A lamp behind your subject becomes a back light. Start simple and add equipment only when you understand why you need it.</p>

    <h3>Color Temperature Matters</h3>
    <p>Light comes in different colors. Warm light (tungsten/incandescent) is around 3200K. Daylight is around 5600K. If you mix these in one shot without correcting, your video will look unprofessional. Either keep all your lights the same temperature, or use color correction in post-production.</p>

