    <h2>Part 3: Camera and Framing</h2>

    <p>The camera is just a tool. A $4,000 cinema camera and a $800 smartphone can both create compelling content if you know how to use them. What matters is understanding composition and movement.</p>

    <h3>Composition Rules</h3>
    <p>The rule of thirds divides your frame into nine equal sections (3x3 grid). Place your subject on one of the intersecting lines rather than dead center. This creates visual balance and draws the eye naturally through the frame. Most camera phones have a grid overlay option—use it.</p>

    <p>Leading lines guide the viewer's eye through the frame. A road disappearing into the distance, a fence line, a person's gaze—all lead the viewer where you want them to look. Negative space gives your subject room to move or look into. Avoid centering everything and cramping your subject against the frame edge.</p>

    <h3>Camera Movement</h3>
    <p>Static shots are powerful, but thoughtful camera movement adds production value. The key word is "thoughtful"—every movement should serve the story. Never move the camera just to move it. Motivated movement includes:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Pan:</strong> Horizontal camera movement (left to right or vice versa)</li>
      <li><strong>Tilt:</strong> Vertical camera movement (up or down)</li>
      <li><strong>Dolly/Slide:</strong> Moving the camera toward or away from the subject</li>
      <li><strong>Handheld:</strong> Intentional camera shake for energy and urgency</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Slow, smooth movements feel cinematic. Fast movements feel chaotic. Match your movement speed to the mood of your content. Use a tripod, slider, or gimbal to achieve smooth camera movement. Handheld footage shot without stabilization reads as amateurish.</p>

    <h2>Part 4: Audio Production</h2>

    <p>Here's a hard truth: viewers will tolerate mediocre video if the audio is good. They will not tolerate great video with bad audio. Audio is 50% of the experience. Invest here.</p>

    <h3>Microphone Selection</h3>
    <p>For on-camera talent, a lavalier microphone (lapel mic) placed 6 inches from your mouth captures clean, direct sound. For interview setups, a larger condenser mic on a boom pole works well. For voiceover, any reasonably quiet room and a standard USB microphone will do—what matters is distance (6-12 inches away) and consistency.</p>

    <p>Phone microphones and camera built-in mics are last resorts. They pick up everything—wind, room noise, camera clicks. A $30 lavalier mic connected to your phone will transform your audio quality.</p>

    <h3>Audio Environment</h3>
    <p>Hard surfaces reflect sound and create echo. Carpet, curtains, blankets, and foam panels absorb sound and reduce reflections. The best audio setup isn't expensive—it's intentional. Record in a smaller room with soft materials rather than a cavernous space with hard walls.</p>

